arch:property.oc:show_val: Fill layer in the southeast of the trench. Between the two pits in the walls. It was originally a part of L158, but there is evidence of ash deposits and bricks in this locus; this signifies that it could differ from L158. The bricks originally present in the northwest corner of this locus did not continue down into the locus, indicating that they were probably there from wall collapse or something similar. When the locus reached the layer of the pit to its southeast, it was decided that the locus had not ended and the bottom of the put was the same. Thus we extended the locus to include everything southeast of the locus and south of the wall to the southern baulk. Once excavation reached about 15cm, some bricks extending from wall L157 in the very north of the locus became apparent. There were only two bricks, and they do not connect to anything. The brick is also visible in the section of the wall that these bricks touch. Possibly these are from wall collapse, like the ones previously visible at the top of the locus, or from some construction or feature. The bricks visible at the top of the locus were directly above these lower bricks.
poorly sorted, sticky and few rocky inclusions

arch:note.arch:string: Contexts excavated in trenches were recorded using the "locus system." A locus is any discrete three-dimensional entity excavated in a trench. The key to the locus system is the recognition that a locus is any one thing. Differences in soil composition or texture are therefore as important as, for example, the difference between a pit and a wall. If two entities were distinct, they were considered separate loci and were therefore assigned separate locus numbers. It should also be noted that every context excavated in a trench was given a locus number and thus the trench itself is made up completely of excavated loci.
